	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64278870"><p>This assumes that obviously self driving cars are safer than humans, but I don't know that we have the data to bear that out yet.</p><p>Currently, the self driving experience is highly restricted and on rails.  When in doubt, the self driving systems will refuse to drive. As close as we get to self-driving cars, they are all newer cars without maintenance issues.</p><p>Tesla repeatedly trots out miles driven as "apples to apples" despite opting out of adversarial conditions that cause the most human incidents.</p><p>Also a question of how much forced human engagement can help cover. It might be that "eyes on road, hands on wheel" nanny combined with "self driving" results in the most safety, even if that's unappealing because the human operator wanted to do other things.</p></div>
	</div>

